  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Memorial Regarding an Envoy's Inquiry and Felicitations
  author: Kim Bu-il
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly understand that when the Son of Heaven cherishes his lords, he yet maintains the virtue of care and remembrance. How then could the feudal states forget the ancient custom of envoys' inquiries when serving the greater realm? Thus do I now, following the precedents of old, presume to submit this humble memorial.

    Your servant, ruling a small domain in the eastern region as an outer vassal to the Middle Kingdom, could not hasten to court when the Two Sagacious Ones undertook their distant campaigns. When His Majesty later ascended the throne, I remained unable to present felicitations at the gate of the palace. In the year Mushin, the State Envoy Yang Yingcheng and others arrived with radiant splendor, conveying the imperial words of instruction, requesting that our small state borrow the road to welcome the imperial carriage. Though the command issued with great authority, the circumstances made it difficult to comply fully. So I sent forth a modest embassy bearing only sincere devotion. Though I, like the people of Yue, possess meager talents, my heart has been consumed only with reverence and anxiety. Yet the Great Emperor, possessed of boundless magnanimity, has specially extended the grace of forgiveness. My gratitude overflows without cease, and I pledge myself entirely to loyalty.

    Moreover, in the year Gyeongsul, the Special Envoy Wang Jeong-chung brought an imperial edict stating that when the border troubles are calmed, we shall inquire of the time for your embassy. Receiving these solemn instructions with utmost respect, though I dare not yet perform the full rites of tributary homage, I am so moved by this supreme benevolence that I now lay bare this ant-like heart before the celestial throne, humbly entreating its gaze.

    While I look up to the Zhou house with reverence, I blush that my service cannot match the great achievements of the Duke of Jin of old. Yet I trust that, remaining loyal within the Han court, I shall not diminish the ancient relationship of Joseon.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Two Sagacious Ones' likely refers to previous rulers of China; 'the gate of the palace' (闕庭) is a traditional term for the imperial court.
    - The reference to 'people of Yue' and 'Duke of Jin' are classical allusions emphasizing humility and historical precedent in the tributary relationship.
    - This memorial exemplifies the formal diplomatic language used by Korean rulers in their communications with China, expressing both deference and the maintenance of dignified sovereignty.
